<section xml:id="group">
  <title>Introduction to groups</title>
  
  <definition xml:id="def-group">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>group</term> is a set <m>G</m> along with a binary algebraic operation <m>\cdot</m> 
        that satisfies the following properties:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Closure:</em> For any <m>a,b</m> in <m>G</m>, it follows that <m>a\cdot b</m> in <m>G</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Associativity:</em> For any <m>a,b, c</m> in <m>G</m>, it follows that <m>(a\cdot b)\cdot c = a\cdot (b\cdot c)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Identity:</em> There is an element (usually denoted) <m>e</m> in <m>G</m>, such that for any <m>a</m> in <m>G</m>, 
              we have that <m>e\cdot a=a</m> and <m>a\cdot e=a</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>Inverses:</em> For any <m>a</m> in <m>G</m>, we there is a <m>a^{-1}</m> in <m>G</m> so that <m>a\cdot a^{-1}=e</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <problem xml:id="problem-maybegroups">
